<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-converting-non-linear-equations-into-a-linear-form" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Converting Non-Linear Equations into a Linear Form</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.6 Graphical Methods
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Convert nonlinear equation to linear form in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    20 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To discover that a curved graph can be straightened by changing which variable is plotted on one axis.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Provide each group with the braking distance data. Guide them to plot <m>d</m> against <m>v</m> first, then against <m>v^2</m>. The contrast between the two graphs — one curved, one straight — is the key discovery. Ask: "What changed? What did we plot differently?"
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                A road safety researcher measured the braking distance <m>d</m> (in metres) of a car travelling at different speeds <m>v</m> (in km/h) on a dry road. The results are shown below.
            </p>
            <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                <row>
                    <cell>Speed <m>v</m> (km/h)</cell>
                    <cell>10</cell><cell>20</cell><cell>30</cell><cell>40</cell><cell>50</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Braking distance <m>d</m> (m)</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell><cell>4</cell><cell>9</cell><cell>16</cell><cell>25</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do:</alert>
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Plot a graph of <m>d</m> against <m>v</m>. Describe the shape of the graph.</p></li>
                <li><p>Add a third row to the table and compute the value of <m>v^2</m> for each speed.</p></li>
                <li><p>Plot a graph of <m>d</m> against <m>v^2</m>. Describe this graph.</p></li>
                <li><p>The researcher believes the model is <m>d = kv^2</m>. What does your second graph tell you about this claim?</p></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the three main linearisation techniques: algebraic substitution, log-log transformation, and semi-log transformation.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Connect the activity directly to the general method: "We changed the horizontal axis from <m>v</m> to <m>v^2</m>. This is the same as substituting <m>X = v^2</m>, so <m>d = kv^2</m> becomes <m>d = kX</m> — a straight line through the origin." Then introduce the two logarithmic forms using the insight below.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <title>Key Ideas</title>
        <p>
            Many real-world relationships are not linear — they produce curves when plotted. We can <em>linearise</em> a non-linear equation by choosing what to plot on each axis so that the graph becomes a straight line.
        </p>
        <p>
            The three most important non-linear forms, and how to linearise them, are shown below.
        </p>
        <tabular halign="center" bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Non-linear equation</cell>
                <cell>Plot on vertical axis</cell>
                <cell>Plot on horizontal axis</cell>
                <cell>Resulting linear equation</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y = ax^2 + c</m></cell>
                <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                <cell><m>x^2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>y = a(x^2) + c</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y = ax^n</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log y</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log y = n\log x + \log a</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y = ab^x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log y</m></cell>
                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\log y = (\log b)\,x + \log a</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
        <p>
            In each case, the transformed graph is a straight line of the form <m>Y = mX + c</m>. Notice that for <m>y = ax^n</m> we take logs of <em>both</em> variables, while for <m>y = ab^x</m> we only take the log of <m>y</m>.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <title>Linearising <m>y = ax^2 + c</m></title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A farmer measures the area <m>A</m> (m²) of several circular crop plots of different radii <m>r</m> (m). The areas follow the model <m>A = kr^2</m>.
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Show how <m>A = kr^2</m> can be written in linear form, and state what should be plotted on each axis to obtain a straight line.</p></li>
                <li><p>The farmer's plot of <m>A</m> against <m>r^2</m> passes through <m>(0,\; 0)</m> and <m>(25,\; 78.5)</m>. Find the value of <m>k</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>X = r^2</m>. The equation becomes
                            <md>
                                <mrow>A = kX</mrow>
                            </md>
                            which is a straight line through the origin. Plot <m>A</m> on the vertical axis and <m>r^2</m> on the horizontal axis.
                        </p>
                        <sidebyside widths="48% 48%" margins="auto">
                            <figure xml:id="fig-linearise-quad-curve">
                                <caption>A graph of <m>A</m> against <m>r</m> gives a curve.</caption>
                                <image width="100%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                        \begin{axis}[
                                        grid=both,
                                        minor grid style={draw=gray!15, line width=0.2pt},
                                        major grid style={draw=gray!40, line width=0.4pt},
                                        minor tick num=1,
                                        axis lines=left,
                                        xlabel={$r$ (m)},
                                        ylabel={$A$ (m$^2$)},
                                        xmin=0, xmax=5.5, ymin=0, ymax=90,
                                        xtick={0,1,2,3,4,5},
                                        ytick={0,20,40,60,80},
                                        width=6.5cm, height=7cm,
                                        tick label style={font=\small},
                                        label style={font=\small}
                                        ]
                                        \addplot[blue, very thick, domain=0:5, samples=60] {pi*x^2};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue, mark size=2pt]
                                        coordinates {(1,3.14) (2,12.57) (3,28.27) (4,50.27) (5,78.54)};
                                        \end{axis}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-linearise-quad-line">
                                <caption>A graph of <m>A</m> against <m>r^2</m> gives a straight line.</caption>
                                <image width="100%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                        \begin{axis}[
                                        grid=both,
                                        minor grid style={draw=gray!15, line width=0.2pt},
                                        major grid style={draw=gray!40, line width=0.4pt},
                                        minor tick num=1,
                                        axis lines=left,
                                        xlabel={$r^2$ (m$^2$)},
                                        ylabel={$A$ (m$^2$)},
                                        xmin=0, xmax=27, ymin=0, ymax=90,
                                        xtick={0,5,10,15,20,25},
                                        ytick={0,20,40,60,80},
                                        width=6.5cm, height=7cm,
                                        tick label style={font=\small},
                                        label style={font=\small}
                                        ]
                                        \addplot[blue, very thick] coordinates {(0,0) (25,78.54)};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue, mark size=2pt]
                                        coordinates {(1,3.14) (4,12.57) (9,28.27) (16,50.27) (25,78.54)};
                                        \end{axis}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </sidebyside>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The line passes through <m>(0, 0)</m> and <m>(25, 78.5)</m>, so
                            <md>
                                <mrow>k = \frac{78.5}{25} = 3.14</mrow>
                            </md>
                            This is consistent with <m>k = \pi \approx 3.14</m>, confirming that the area formula for a circle is <m>A = \pi r^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Linearising <m>y = ax^n</m></title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A student investigates how the period <m>T</m> (seconds) of a simple pendulum depends on its length <m>L</m> (metres). The data recorded is shown below.
            </p>
            <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>L</m> (m)</cell>
                    <cell>0.25</cell><cell>1.00</cell><cell>2.25</cell><cell>4.00</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>T</m> (s)</cell>
                    <cell>1.00</cell><cell>2.00</cell><cell>3.00</cell><cell>4.00</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                The student believes the relationship has the form <m>T = kL^n</m>.
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Show how <m>T = kL^n</m> can be written in linear form and state what to plot on each axis.</p></li>
                <li><p>Copy and complete the table of logarithms below, then plot <m>\log_{10} T</m> against <m>\log_{10} L</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Use the graph to find the values of <m>n</m> and <m>k</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Taking <m>\log_{10}</m> of both sides:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\log_{10} T \amp= \log_{10}(kL^n)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\log_{10} T \amp= n\log_{10} L + \log_{10} k</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Plotting <m>\log_{10} T</m> on the vertical axis and <m>\log_{10} L</m> on the horizontal axis gives a straight line.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Computing logarithms (to 2 decimal places):
                        </p>
                        <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>\log_{10} L</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-0.60</m></cell><cell><m>0.00</m></cell><cell><m>0.35</m></cell><cell><m>0.60</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>\log_{10} T</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>0.00</m></cell><cell><m>0.30</m></cell><cell><m>0.48</m></cell><cell><m>0.60</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                        <sidebyside widths="48% 48%" margins="auto">
                            <figure xml:id="fig-linearise-power-curve">
                                <caption>A graph of <m>T</m> against <m>L</m> gives a curve.</caption>
                                <image width="100%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                        \begin{axis}[
                                        grid=both,
                                        minor grid style={draw=gray!15, line width=0.2pt},
                                        major grid style={draw=gray!40, line width=0.4pt},
                                        minor tick num=1,
                                        axis lines=left,
                                        xlabel={$L$ (m)},
                                        ylabel={$T$ (s)},
                                        xmin=0, xmax=4.5, ymin=0, ymax=4.5,
                                        xtick={0,1,2,3,4},
                                        ytick={0,1,2,3,4},
                                        width=6.5cm, height=7cm,
                                        tick label style={font=\small},
                                        label style={font=\small}
                                        ]
                                        \addplot[blue, very thick, domain=0:4.3, samples=60] {2*sqrt(x)};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue, mark size=2pt]
                                        coordinates {(0.25,1) (1,2) (2.25,3) (4,4)};
                                        \end{axis}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-linearise-power-line">
                                <caption>A graph of <m>\log_{10} T</m> against <m>\log_{10} L</m> gives a straight line.</caption>
                                <image width="100%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                        \begin{axis}[
                                        grid=major,
                                        major grid style={draw=gray!40, line width=0.4pt},
                                        axis lines=left,
                                        xlabel={$\log_{10} L$},
                                        ylabel={$\log_{10} T$},
                                        xmin=-0.7, xmax=0.7, ymin=0, ymax=0.7,
                                        xtick={-0.6,-0.3,0,0.3,0.6},
                                        ytick={0,0.2,0.4,0.6},
                                        width=6.5cm, height=7cm,
                                        tick label style={font=\small},
                                        label style={font=\small}
                                        ]
                                        \addplot[blue, very thick] coordinates {(-0.65,-0.025) (0.65,0.625)};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue, mark size=2pt]
                                        coordinates {(-0.60,0.00) (0.00,0.30) (0.35,0.48) (0.60,0.60)};
                                        \end{axis}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </sidebyside>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the end points <m>(-0.60,\; 0.00)</m> and <m>(0.60,\; 0.60)</m>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>n = \frac{0.60 - 0.00}{0.60 - (-0.60)} = \frac{0.60}{1.20} = 0.5</mrow>
                            </md>
                            At <m>\log_{10} L = 0</m> the line gives <m>\log_{10} k = 0.30</m>, so
                            <md>
                                <mrow>k = 10^{0.30} \approx 2.0</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Therefore <m>T = 2.0\,L^{0.5} = 2\sqrt{L}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Linearising <m>y = ab^x</m></title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The amount <m>A</m> (Ksh thousands) in a mobile savings account after <m>t</m> months is modelled by <m>A = P \cdot b^t</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                A graph of <m>\log_{10} A</m> against <m>t</m> is a straight line passing through <m>(0,\; 2.00)</m> and <m>(6,\; 2.48)</m>.
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Show how <m>A = Pb^t</m> can be written in linear form and state what to plot on each axis.</p></li>
                <li><p>Find the values of <m>P</m> and <m>b</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Taking <m>\log_{10}</m> of both sides:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\log_{10} A \amp= \log_{10}(P \cdot b^t)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\log_{10} A \amp= (\log_{10} b)\, t + \log_{10} P</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Plot <m>\log_{10} A</m> on the vertical axis and <m>t</m> on the horizontal axis.
                        </p>
                        <sidebyside widths="48% 48%" margins="auto">
                            <figure xml:id="fig-linearise-exp-curve">
                                <caption>A graph of <m>A</m> against <m>t</m> gives a curve.</caption>
                                <image width="100%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                        \begin{axis}[
                                        grid=both,
                                        minor grid style={draw=gray!15, line width=0.2pt},
                                        major grid style={draw=gray!40, line width=0.4pt},
                                        minor tick num=1,
                                        axis lines=left,
                                        xlabel={$t$ (months)},
                                        ylabel={$A$ (Ksh thousands)},
                                        xmin=0, xmax=6.5, ymin=0, ymax=320,
                                        xtick={0,1,2,3,4,5,6},
                                        ytick={0,50,100,150,200,250,300},
                                        width=6.5cm, height=7cm,
                                        tick label style={font=\small},
                                        label style={font=\small}
                                        ]
                                        \addplot[blue, very thick, domain=0:6, samples=60] {100*(1.2^x)};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue, mark size=2pt]
                                        coordinates {(0,100) (6,298.6)};
                                        \end{axis}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-linearise-exp-line">
                                <caption>A graph of <m>\log_{10} A</m> against <m>t</m> gives a straight line.</caption>
                                <image width="100%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                        \begin{axis}[
                                        grid=both,
                                        minor grid style={draw=gray!15, line width=0.2pt},
                                        major grid style={draw=gray!40, line width=0.4pt},
                                        minor tick num=1,
                                        axis lines=left,
                                        xlabel={$t$ (months)},
                                        ylabel={$\log_{10} A$},
                                        xmin=0, xmax=6.5, ymin=1.95, ymax=2.55,
                                        xtick={0,1,2,3,4,5,6},
                                        ytick={2.0,2.1,2.2,2.3,2.4,2.5},
                                        width=6.5cm, height=7cm,
                                        tick label style={font=\small},
                                        label style={font=\small}
                                        ]
                                        \addplot[blue, very thick] coordinates {(0,2.00) (6,2.48)};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue, mark size=2pt]
                                        coordinates {(0,2.00) (6,2.48)};
                                        \end{axis}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </sidebyside>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            From the point <m>(0,\; 2.00)</m>, the vertical intercept gives <m>\log_{10} P = 2.00</m>, so
                            <md>
                                <mrow>P = 10^{2.00} = 100</mrow>
                            </md>
                            The initial amount is Ksh 100 000.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Using both points to find <m>\log_{10} b</m>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\log_{10} b = \frac{2.48 - 2.00}{6 - 0} = \frac{0.48}{6} = 0.08</mrow>
                            </md>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>b = 10^{0.08} \approx 1.20</mrow>
                            </md>
                            The account grows by approximately 20% each month.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> satisfy the equation <m>y = ax^2 + c</m>.
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Write the equation in linear form and state what should be plotted on each axis to give a straight line.</p></li>
                        <li><p>A straight line is obtained by plotting <m>y</m> against <m>x^2</m>. The line passes through the points <m>(1,\; 5)</m> and <m>(9,\; 21)</m>. Find the values of <m>a</m> and <m>c</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>The equation is <m>y = a(x^2) + c</m>. Plot <m>y</m> on the vertical axis and <m>x^2</m> on the horizontal axis.</p></li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Using the two points: <m>a = \dfrac{21 - 5}{9 - 1} = \dfrac{16}{8} = 2</m>.
                                Substituting back: <m>5 = 2(1) + c</m>, so <m>c = 3</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Given <m>y = ax^2 + c</m>, let <m>X = x^2</m>.
                                The linear form is <m>y = aX + c</m>.
                                We plot <m>y</m> on the vertical axis and <m>x^2</m> on the horizontal axis.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The points are <m>(1, 5)</m> and <m>(9, 21)</m> on the <m>(x^2, y)</m> plane.
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\text{Gradient } a \amp= \frac{21 - 5}{9 - 1} = \frac{16}{8} = 2</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\text{Intercept } c \amp: 5 = 2(1) + c \implies c = 3</mrow>
                                </md>
                                The original equation is <m>y = 2x^2 + 3</m>.
                            </p>
                            <image width="65%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[
                                        axis lines=left,
                                        xlabel={$x^2$},
                                        ylabel={$y$},
                                        xmin=0, xmax=10,
                                        ymin=0, ymax=25,
                                        xtick={0,2,4,6,8,10},
                                        ytick={0,5,10,15,20,25},
                                        tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                                        grid=both,
                                        grid style={line width=0.2pt, draw=gray!30},
                                    ]
                                        \addplot[blue, thick, domain=0:10] {2*x + 3};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, red] coordinates {(1,5) (9,21)};
                                        \node[below right, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:1,5) {$(1,5)$};
                                        \node[above left, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:9,21) {$(9,21)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two variables are related by <m>y = ax^n</m>.
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Show how to write this equation in linear form, and state what to plot on each axis.</p></li>
                        <li><p>A plot of <m>\log_{10} y</m> against <m>\log_{10} x</m> gives a straight line through <m>(0.5,\; 1.9)</m> and <m>(1.5,\; 3.1)</m>. Find the values of <m>a</m> and <m>n</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Take <m>\log_{10}</m> of both sides: <m>\log_{10} y = n\log_{10} x + \log_{10} a</m>. Plot <m>\log_{10} y</m> on the vertical axis and <m>\log_{10} x</m> on the horizontal axis.</p></li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>n = \dfrac{3.1 - 1.9}{1.5 - 0.5} = 1.2</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\log_{10} a = 1.9 - 1.2 \times 0.5 = 1.3</m>, so <m>a = 10^{1.3} \approx 20</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Given <m>y = ax^n</m>, taking logs gives <m>\log y = n \log x + \log a</m>.
                                We plot <m>\log y</m> on the vertical axis and <m>\log x</m> on the horizontal axis.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Using the points <m>(0.5, 1.9)</m> and <m>(1.5, 3.1)</m>:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>n \amp= \frac{3.1 - 1.9}{1.5 - 0.5} = 1.2</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\log a \amp= 1.9 - 1.2(0.5) = 1.3 \implies a = 10^{1.3} \approx 20</mrow>
                                </md>
                                The equation is <m>y = 20x^{1.2}</m>.
                            </p>
                            <image width="65%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[
                                        axis lines=left,
                                        xlabel={$\log x$},
                                        ylabel={$\log y$},
                                        xmin=0, xmax=2,
                                        ymin=0, ymax=4,
                                        xtick={0,0.5,1,1.5,2},
                                        ytick={0,1,2,3,4},
                                        tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                                        grid=both,
                                        grid style={line width=0.2pt, draw=gray!30},
                                    ]
                                        \addplot[blue, thick, domain=0:2] {1.2*x + 1.3};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, red] coordinates {(0.5,1.9) (1.5,3.1)};
                                    \end{axis}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A colony of bacteria grows according to <m>N = N_0 \cdot r^t</m>, where <m>N</m> is the number of bacteria after <m>t</m> hours.
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Write <m>N = N_0 \cdot r^t</m> in linear form and state what to plot on each axis.</p></li>
                        <li><p>A researcher's plot of <m>\log_{10} N</m> against <m>t</m> passes through <m>(0,\; 3.0)</m> and <m>(4,\; 3.6)</m>. Find the initial population <m>N_0</m> and the growth factor <m>r</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Take logs: <m>\log_{10} N = (\log_{10} r)\,t + \log_{10} N_0</m>. Plot <m>\log_{10} N</m> on the vertical axis and <m>t</m> on the horizontal axis.</p></li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Intercept: <m>\log_{10} N_0 = 3.0</m>, so <m>N_0 = 1000</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\log_{10} r = \dfrac{3.6 - 3.0}{4 - 0} = 0.15</m>, so <m>r = 10^{0.15} \approx 1.41</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Given <m>N = N_0 \cdot r^t</m>, taking logs gives <m>\log N = (\log r)t + \log N_0</m>.
                                This is a straight line if we plot <m>\log N</m> against <m>t</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The points are <m>(0, 3.0)</m> and <m>(4, 3.6)</m> on the <m>(t, \log N)</m> plane.
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\text{Intercept } \log N_0 \amp= 3.0 \implies N_0 = 10^3 = 1000</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\text{Gradient } \log r \amp= \frac{3.6 - 3.0}{4 - 0} = 0.15 \implies r = 10^{0.15} \approx 1.41</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <image width="65%">
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[
                                        axis lines=left,
                                        xlabel={$t$},
                                        ylabel={$\log N$},
                                        xmin=0, xmax=5,
                                        ymin=2.5, ymax=4,
                                        xtick={0,1,2,3,4,5},
                                        ytick={3.0,3.2,3.4,3.6,3.8},
                                        tick label style={font=\footnotesize},
                                        grid=both,
                                        grid style={line width=0.2pt, draw=gray!30},
                                    ]
                                        \addplot[blue, thick, domain=0:5] {0.15*x + 3.0};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, red] coordinates {(0,3.0) (4,3.6)};
                                    \end{axis}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each equation below, state what should be plotted on each axis to obtain a straight line, and write the resulting linear equation.
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>y = 5x^2 - 3</m></li>
                        <li><m>y = 4x^{0.5}</m></li>
                        <li><m>y = 2 \cdot 3^x</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Plot <m>y</m> against <m>x^2</m>. Linear equation: <m>y = 5(x^2) - 3</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Plot <m>\log_{10} y</m> against <m>\log_{10} x</m>. Linear equation: <m>\log_{10} y = 0.5\log_{10} x + \log_{10} 4</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Plot <m>\log_{10} y</m> against <m>x</m>. Linear equation: <m>\log_{10} y = (\log_{10} 3)\,x + \log_{10} 2</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Focus on <m>y = ax^2 + c</m> only. Provide a simple template: "replace <m>x^2</m> with <m>X</m> to get <m>y = aX + c</m>." Use the braking distance activity data for guided practice.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        All three forms. Emphasise recognising <em>which</em> transformation applies — the key question is whether both variables need logs (<m>y = ax^n</m>) or only the output variable (<m>y = ab^x</m>).
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Ask students to explain, in their own words, why <m>y = ax^n</m> requires a log-log plot while <m>y = ab^x</m> only requires a semi-log plot. Encourage them to test their understanding with a new equation of their own choosing.
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

